WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.958
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:07.910
SPEAKER 1: Well, thank
you for being here.

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:09.670
Thank you, DC Comics.

00:00:09.670 --> 00:00:13.360
So I wanted to start by asking a
general question to all of you.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:15.430
What does Superman stand for?

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:19.940
And why has he been a fan
favorite for 80 years?

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:20.440
Who's brave?

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:21.860
PAUL DINI: Well, when
you're that strong,

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:23.180
you don't stand for much.

00:00:23.180 --> 00:00:24.110
SPEAKER 1: [LAUGHS]

00:00:24.110 --> 00:00:25.442
PAUL DINI: Sorry, bad joke.

00:00:25.442 --> 00:00:26.900
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Well, hope is

00:00:26.900 --> 00:00:30.540
what he stands for in
the most general sense.

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:33.080
And that's why the character
has lasted long because you

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:34.580
can't argue with that.

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:35.300
It's inarguable.

00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:36.510
Hope is good.

00:00:36.510 --> 00:00:37.790
So, yeah.

00:00:37.790 --> 00:00:38.540
SPEAKER 1: Agreed.

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:40.045
DAN JURGENS: Moral integrity.

00:00:40.045 --> 00:00:40.711
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:00:40.711 --> 00:00:43.090
DAN JURGENS: Yeah, which
extends to everything.

00:00:43.090 --> 00:00:46.455
MARV WOLFMAN: Truth without
looking for a reward.

00:00:49.065 --> 00:00:51.120
PAUL DINI: Yeah, he
stands for the future.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:57.850
He puts himself up there
as a suggestion of what

00:00:57.850 --> 00:00:59.520
mankind could look toward.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:01.460
And he doesn't force
anybody to do that.

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:05.039
But he's out there and
seeks to inspire people.

00:01:05.039 --> 00:01:06.830
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Yeah, and also truth,

00:01:06.830 --> 00:01:08.440
justice, and the American way.

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:12.940
This is a phrase synonymous
with Superman for decades.

00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:16.750
And it's just one of those
almost cliche things.

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:19.449
But now in this day and
age, truth and justice

00:01:19.449 --> 00:01:21.490
and the American way--
they mean different things

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:22.390
to different people.

00:01:22.390 --> 00:01:22.750
SPEAKER 1: Right.

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:24.916
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: And
some of it is under siege.

00:01:24.916 --> 00:01:31.235
And so writing a character
who believes in them so much--

00:01:31.235 --> 00:01:33.130
it's actually a great
way to spend your day.

00:01:33.130 --> 00:01:35.030
MARV WOLFMAN: Well, it's
completely ingrained in him.

00:01:35.030 --> 00:01:35.470
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Yeah, oh yeah.

00:01:35.470 --> 00:01:37.300
MARV WOLFMAN: He doesn't
have to think about doing it.

00:01:37.300 --> 00:01:38.130
He just does it.

00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:39.536
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yep.

00:01:39.536 --> 00:01:41.980
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, and we
need that always, especially

00:01:41.980 --> 00:01:42.580
right now.

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:43.480
PAUL DINI: Exactly.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:44.890
SPEAKER 1: So do
you guys see him

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:47.710
more as the Boy Scout
figure he has kind of been

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:50.710
for a long time or
more as the prominently

00:01:50.710 --> 00:01:54.580
alien counter-cultural
figure he's been recently

00:01:54.580 --> 00:01:57.412
and perhaps was originally?

00:01:57.412 --> 00:01:59.870
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Well, I
don't see him as a Boy Scout.

00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:03.150
That was the question
as the new Spider--

00:02:03.150 --> 00:02:05.000
Spider-Man-- Superman, rather.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:05.440
DAN JURGENS: Wait, wait, wait.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:05.870
What was that?

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:06.610
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: I'm
still writing Spider-Man--

00:02:06.610 --> 00:02:07.880
PAUL DINI: Oh, yeah.

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:08.820
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
It's going to be a while.

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:10.569
I'm still writing
Spider-Man on my checks.

00:02:10.569 --> 00:02:21.290
But with Superman comes a great
deal of empathy and pathos.

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:24.530
And sometimes people
can relate to that

00:02:24.530 --> 00:02:26.097
as vanilla or Boy Scout.

00:02:26.097 --> 00:02:27.930
And nothing could be
further from the truth.

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:30.760
And I remember, like, when I was
writing, like, Captain America

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:33.229
or Cyclops, they would
say the same thing and go,

00:02:33.229 --> 00:02:34.520
isn't that a vanilla character?

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:36.910
I'd go, oh, no, no, no, no.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:41.970
Those characters are the most
interesting to peel back on.

00:02:41.970 --> 00:02:44.390
As someone who can stand
there and has the guts

00:02:44.390 --> 00:02:47.210
to be a Boy Scout, there's
a lot going on in there.

00:02:47.210 --> 00:02:50.840
And to peel it back and show
you how relatable it is,

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:51.754
is quite something.

00:02:51.754 --> 00:02:54.170
MARV WOLFMAN: Well, to call
someone a Boy Scout in the way

00:02:54.170 --> 00:02:55.895
they mean it means
they're bland.

00:02:55.895 --> 00:02:57.020
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:02:57.020 --> 00:02:58.519
MARV WOLFMAN: And
that's ridiculous.

00:02:58.519 --> 00:03:00.560
A character who is just
trying to do good, who's

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:02.000
trying to do the right thing--

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.190
if you say that's bland,
if you say that's bad,

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:06.710
you're saying doing
the right thing is bad.

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:09.110
But doing the wrong
thing is cool.

00:03:09.110 --> 00:03:11.470
And that's totally the wrong
message for the character.

00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:13.981
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Totally.

00:03:13.981 --> 00:03:15.730
PAUL DINI: I've always
thought of him as--

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:18.100
there was a line, I think,
in one of the early Fleischer

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:19.690
Superman cartoons.

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:22.450
There was a race of Supermen
from the planet Krypton.

00:03:22.450 --> 00:03:24.790
And I've always felt that
there was something about him,

00:03:24.790 --> 00:03:28.690
maybe either
spiritually or even just

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:31.420
in the way the
Kryptonians evolved,

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:34.810
that they look ahead, that
they look out for each other.

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:37.540
They look toward
the better things.

00:03:37.540 --> 00:03:41.980
Whereas humans might see crime
as an option or something

00:03:41.980 --> 00:03:45.580
to consider, that's
not the Kryptonian way.

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:48.890
It would be abhorrent
to think that way.

00:03:48.890 --> 00:03:52.270
And I think that he personifies
the best of that nature

00:03:52.270 --> 00:03:55.750
and is trying to put it out
there as a way of saying,

00:03:55.750 --> 00:03:57.275
this is where I come from.

00:03:57.275 --> 00:03:58.790
And this is what I do.

00:03:58.790 --> 00:04:03.794
And I think he was lucky enough
to find adopted parents who

00:04:03.794 --> 00:04:04.960
fostered that belief in him.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:07.130
SPEAKER 1: Mm-hm.

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:08.070
Anything to add, Dan?

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:09.840
DAN JURGENS: No,
only that to me,

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:12.500
the Boy Scout thing-- he only
ever had a couple of villains

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:14.750
refer to him as a
Boy Scout, if any.

00:04:14.750 --> 00:04:17.540
That was always something that
came up on the part of fans.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:19.902
And they meant it in
a derogatory sense.

00:04:19.902 --> 00:04:21.860
And I always thought was
remarkably unfortunate

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:23.780
because, yeah, it's true.

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:27.700
If we're to say it's bad to try
and embrace the best qualities,

00:04:27.700 --> 00:04:29.542
there's something
totally wrong with that.

00:04:29.542 --> 00:04:30.250
PAUL DINI: Mm-hm.

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:32.040
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah,
but the struggle to do it

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:33.260
is not a vanilla struggle.

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:33.735
DAN JURGENS: No, not at all.

00:04:33.735 --> 00:04:35.401
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
It's insanely hard

00:04:35.401 --> 00:04:36.440
to do what he's doing.

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:40.010
So I always, like, bat
that away as not even

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:43.319
worth discussing because it's so
obvious what a struggle it is.

00:04:43.319 --> 00:04:44.110
DAN JURGENS: Right.

00:04:44.110 --> 00:04:44.790
PAUL DINI: Yeah.

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:47.300
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, so see,
being good is cool, guys.

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:49.100
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:52.250
SPEAKER 1: So it's probably safe
to assume that most Superman

00:04:52.250 --> 00:04:55.610
fans obviously cannot fly
or bench press the Earth.

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:59.560
So what do you think
makes Superman relatable?

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:02.310
DAN JURGENS: I think it's the
fact that he is one of us.

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:04.860
And if you go back to his
creation and this idea that

00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:08.550
here is this kind of like farm
kid in the middle of the United

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:13.380
States in Kansas that I
thought at that time, in 1938,

00:05:13.380 --> 00:05:17.430
that becomes representative
of what we were thinking

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:18.750
America was at that point.

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:21.280
It was much more typical
then than it is now.

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:27.000
But at the same time, I think
that is very much who he is--

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.700
this farm kid who grew up
with a respect for life

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:33.330
because if you live on a farm,
you have animals around you

00:05:33.330 --> 00:05:33.980
all the time.

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:34.938
They come, and they go.

00:05:34.938 --> 00:05:35.660
They die.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:38.280
There's all sorts of things
with the planting season

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:39.270
that comes and goes.

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:42.840
And everything lives and
dies and is born again stuff.

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:44.386
And I think because
of that, that

00:05:44.386 --> 00:05:46.802
is something that has always
been imbued in the character.

00:05:49.741 --> 00:05:51.157
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Marv agrees.

00:05:51.157 --> 00:05:52.558
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:05:52.558 --> 00:05:53.960
SPEAKER 1: Thanks, Brian.

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:54.850
You're his assistant.

00:05:54.850 --> 00:05:57.040
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Yeah, I'm his hype man.

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:58.870
SPEAKER 1: So how
do you understand

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:00.880
Superman's relationship
with Batman,

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:04.270
Wonder Woman, and the rest
of the Justice League?

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:07.060
MARV WOLFMAN: I think it's a
matter of seeing people trying

00:06:07.060 --> 00:06:10.900
to accomplish the same goals,
but watching them do it

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:13.210
in a different way,
and the realization

00:06:13.210 --> 00:06:17.560
that you can't have people do
everything you want them to.

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:19.570
Everybody has the right
to go their own way.

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:21.720
But their mission is the same.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:24.520
SPEAKER 1: Right.

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:26.740
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: So
often when you're kids,

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:27.970
you're reading these comics.

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:31.840
And one of the superheroes will
always say, Superman's here.

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:33.230
What are we going to do?

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:33.980
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:06:33.980 --> 00:06:36.146
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: And
so the amount of respect--

00:06:36.146 --> 00:06:38.890
like, physical, and emotional,
and spiritual respect

00:06:38.890 --> 00:06:40.660
they have for
Superman-- is enormous.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:43.735
He is the standard of which they
are all trying to live up to,

00:06:43.735 --> 00:06:46.870
to the point where it's
annoying that he's there,

00:06:46.870 --> 00:06:48.070
because he's constant.

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:49.400
He's always living up to it.

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:54.610
So living up to
that can be immense.

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:58.390
But at the same time, he
seems to respect the others

00:06:58.390 --> 00:07:00.160
in a way they
can't even process.

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:02.260
Like, he goes to Superman--

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:05.020
I mean, he goes to Batman
and Wonder Woman, and goes,

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:07.680
I need help with this, or
you know how to do this.

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:10.607
And I always like that
you've all written scenes

00:07:10.607 --> 00:07:12.940
where they've always seemed,
oh, Superman needs my help.

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:13.560
Oh.

00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:15.370
And I like that.

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:17.140
They genuinely
seem like friends.

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:17.470
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:07:17.470 --> 00:07:17.630
And--

00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:18.200
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
They genuinely

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:19.820
seem to really like each other.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:20.611
DAN JURGENS: Right.

00:07:20.611 --> 00:07:23.771
And Superman never shows
up and says, I'm the guy.

00:07:23.771 --> 00:07:25.270
I think the whole
point is he always

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:27.430
has this sense of
presence about him.

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:29.410
And they respond
to him as the guy.

00:07:29.410 --> 00:07:31.750
But he'd be the last guy
to ever say, I'm the guy,

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:33.070
if that makes sense.

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:34.000
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Which makes him the guy.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:34.590
DAN JURGENS: Right, exactly.

00:07:34.590 --> 00:07:36.673
PAUL DINI: Which makes him
the guy, exactly, yeah.

00:07:36.673 --> 00:07:39.400
MARV WOLFMAN: He's the one
who just his presence inspires

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:40.540
others.

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:43.180
And whether it's the normal
people in Metropolis,

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:46.480
or the world, or
other superheroes,

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:48.010
you want to do well for him.

00:07:48.010 --> 00:07:50.650
You wanted to be the
best because of him.

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:52.600
If he's going to
take you someplace,

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:53.960
you know it's going to be good.

00:07:53.960 --> 00:07:54.190
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Yeah, I think

00:07:54.190 --> 00:07:56.760
you wrote a scene where the
superheroes are like, ugh,

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:58.010
I don't want to do this thing.

00:07:58.010 --> 00:08:00.270
And they're like, all right.

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:02.209
I mean, you can't
not be your best self

00:08:02.209 --> 00:08:03.250
when he's standing there.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.257
You just have to suck it up.

00:08:05.257 --> 00:08:07.840
PAUL DINI: He's the best leader
because he doesn't necessarily

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:08.339
lead.

00:08:08.339 --> 00:08:10.973
He allows the others
to come to the fore.

00:08:10.973 --> 00:08:11.720
DAN JURGENS: Yep.

00:08:11.720 --> 00:08:13.420
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: He lets
Batman think he's leading.

00:08:13.420 --> 00:08:14.086
PAUL DINI: Yeah.

00:08:14.086 --> 00:08:15.690
[CHUCKLING]

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:20.800
SPEAKER 1: So is Clark Kent
or Superman the disguise?

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:22.450
What separates
Clark Kent's persona

00:08:22.450 --> 00:08:24.340
from the Superman persona?

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:25.965
MARV WOLFMAN: I think
they're the same.

00:08:25.965 --> 00:08:28.740
DAN JURGENS: I do, too.

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:31.220
MARV WOLFMAN: Superman,
or rather Kal-El,

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:34.510
came to Earth as an infant.

00:08:34.510 --> 00:08:39.789
All of his morality, all of his
viewpoint comes from the Kents.

00:08:39.789 --> 00:08:41.646
Therefore, he's
the right person.

00:08:41.646 --> 00:08:42.520
He's the real person.

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:44.890
Superman doesn't talk about it.

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:48.640
But he goes out and implements
what the Kents taught him--

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:51.280
to be right, to be
good, to try your best.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:53.380
So I don't see much
of a difference.

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:57.910
Clark is just the
character who isn't flashy.

00:08:57.910 --> 00:09:00.160
But they're both always
trying to do the best.

00:09:02.774 --> 00:09:05.200
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: I think
about that "Kill Bill" bit

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:05.700
often.

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:07.601
I mean, it gets brought
up to us quite a lot.

00:09:07.601 --> 00:09:09.850
Then people think that that's
a statement on Superman.

00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:11.300
And you have to
make a statement.

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:14.830
But my feelings about
it are so different.

00:09:14.830 --> 00:09:17.410
Like even using
the word disguise--

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:19.150
it's like I wouldn't
even use it.

00:09:19.150 --> 00:09:22.660
What I'm a little obsessed
with right now writing them

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:27.760
is that Superman was
kind of thrust on him.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:30.070
Like, his father said,
you are going to do this.

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:33.590
And we're going to
send you to do this.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:37.360
The choice that Clark made in
his life was to be a reporter.

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:39.550
Like, everything else
was thrust upon him.

00:09:39.550 --> 00:09:41.530
Or he was sent to a place.

00:09:41.530 --> 00:09:44.480
But he chose to be a reporter.

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:47.860
He said, there's
truth out there.

00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:50.470
And there's justice to be
had that Superman can't

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:53.650
get to just punching it, right?

00:09:53.650 --> 00:09:54.980
There's another way through it.

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:58.750
And being a writer
to reveal that truth

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:00.080
is something I'm going to do.

00:10:00.080 --> 00:10:02.720
So he chooses to spend
his time doing that.

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:07.210
And I find that
enormously admirable.

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:09.380
It makes me love
him all the more.

00:10:09.380 --> 00:10:14.210
MARV WOLFMAN: And it's something
that all his powers cannot

00:10:14.210 --> 00:10:16.280
alter in any way.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:17.210
He is a writer.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:18.380
He loves being a writer.

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:21.470
He loves telling the story
that he's going to tell.

00:10:21.470 --> 00:10:24.800
And all of his powers
means nothing to him.

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:27.530
It's all about getting
those words down and getting

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:28.730
the thoughts down.

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:30.290
And that's pure Clark.

00:10:30.290 --> 00:10:30.560
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:31.351
DAN JURGENS: Mm-hm.

00:10:31.351 --> 00:10:31.970
Right.

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:36.140
And I think there's a difference
to be drawn between a character

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:39.620
that puts on a mask and
goes and does what he does--

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:40.730
or she does--

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:43.370
because they're making
a conscious decision

00:10:43.370 --> 00:10:45.500
at that point to have
this other identity.

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:47.480
I think with Superman,
I've always looked at it

00:10:47.480 --> 00:10:53.420
as being like someone
who's a police officer,

00:10:53.420 --> 00:10:56.270
or a firefighter, or whatever--

00:10:56.270 --> 00:10:58.116
someone who's in
the military-- where

00:10:58.116 --> 00:10:59.990
this is what they put
on when they wear to go

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:00.570
do what they do.

00:11:00.570 --> 00:11:02.653
But they come home, and
they're still that person.

00:11:02.653 --> 00:11:05.990
And they're not making an effort
to disguise themselves so much.

00:11:05.990 --> 00:11:07.940
So I've always
separated Superman out

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:09.873
from many other
characters that way.

00:11:09.873 --> 00:11:10.860
PAUL DINI: Mm-hm.

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:11.705
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: And
for people who don't know--

00:11:11.705 --> 00:11:13.640
and I'm going to embarrass Dan.

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:17.030
So I had been doing an
insane amount of research.

00:11:17.030 --> 00:11:18.750
And then all of a sudden--

00:11:18.750 --> 00:11:20.510
and I got to know
Dan over the course

00:11:20.510 --> 00:11:23.194
of this whole new
chapter in my life.

00:11:23.194 --> 00:11:24.860
And then you start
going back and, like,

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:27.362
well, the death of Superman
was how many years ago?

00:11:27.362 --> 00:11:28.070
And that wasn't--

00:11:28.070 --> 00:11:28.460
DAN JURGENS: Three.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:28.610
[CHUCKLING]

00:11:28.610 --> 00:11:29.810
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: And
that wasn't his first Superman

00:11:29.810 --> 00:11:30.310
story.

00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:33.110
He's been with
Superman for as long

00:11:33.110 --> 00:11:34.760
as anyone's been
with any character

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:35.900
in the history of comics.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:38.108
Like, people talking about
Chris Claremont and X-Men.

00:11:38.108 --> 00:11:40.340
But what Dan's
accomplished on Superman

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:42.980
is equal, if not
greater, because

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:46.320
of the size of the stories
and what he's accomplished.

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:49.240
So it's quite amazing
what he's done.

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:51.510
And he did it so quietly.

00:11:51.510 --> 00:11:52.510
Like he got to people.

00:11:52.510 --> 00:11:54.440
He kind of just slid in
there and got it done.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:57.110
But here we are, decades
later, with one of the greatest

00:11:57.110 --> 00:11:58.510
achievements with a character.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:11:59.050
So.

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:00.008
DAN JURGENS: Thank you.

00:12:00.008 --> 00:12:01.248
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:12:01.248 --> 00:12:03.558
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:04.944 --> 00:12:06.080
SPEAKER 1: You embarrassed?

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:06.240
DAN JURGENS: Yes.

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:06.740
[LAUGHS]

00:12:06.740 --> 00:12:07.740
PAUL DINI: Little bit.

00:12:07.740 --> 00:12:09.420
DAN JURGENS: It doesn't seem
like it's been that long.

00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:10.169
It really doesn't.

00:12:10.169 --> 00:12:11.250
So, yeah.

00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:13.050
SPEAKER 1: So since
you brought it up, Dan,

00:12:13.050 --> 00:12:16.664
how did it feel
to kill Superman?

00:12:16.664 --> 00:12:19.080
DAN JURGENS: When we started,
it was just a story to tell.

00:12:21.582 --> 00:12:23.040
And we had talked
about it a couple

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:25.410
of times before as let's
do the death of Superman

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.710
because it was a story
we had read in our youth.

00:12:28.710 --> 00:12:30.870
And it had been done
a couple of times.

00:12:30.870 --> 00:12:33.480
And we never had the rest
of the story to go with it.

00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:37.530
And it became a story
that was all about trying

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:39.930
to make a statement
about Superman

00:12:39.930 --> 00:12:41.310
by removing him from the book.

00:12:41.310 --> 00:12:43.410
So we had "Death of Superman."

00:12:43.410 --> 00:12:47.550
After that, it was essentially
"Funeral for a Friend," which

00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:49.530
was the world without Superman.

00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:51.840
That was the story
we wanted to get to.

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:53.400
Before that, the
death of Superman

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:56.126
was just this big, fun exercise.

00:12:56.126 --> 00:12:57.750
But what we wanted
to write about later

00:12:57.750 --> 00:13:00.480
was a world with no Superman.

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:02.460
So at first it was just
this cool story idea.

00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:06.330
But then, as the hype
started to build,

00:13:06.330 --> 00:13:08.530
it really-- as I was writing
and drawing the story,

00:13:08.530 --> 00:13:11.812
you become very
aware that this isn't

00:13:11.812 --> 00:13:13.020
going to be the normal thing.

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:15.750
An awful lot of people are going
to be looking at this book.

00:13:15.750 --> 00:13:17.208
And they're going
to be reading it.

00:13:17.208 --> 00:13:18.720
And everybody was
talking about it.

00:13:18.720 --> 00:13:22.710
And it became a story
element in terms of news,

00:13:22.710 --> 00:13:26.892
even before the book
came out, that it

00:13:26.892 --> 00:13:29.100
felt like there was always
something hanging over me,

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:30.510
especially as I was
drawing the book,

00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:32.885
because it was all splash
pages and everything like that.

00:13:32.885 --> 00:13:35.645
But it was a fun and
magical experience.

00:13:35.645 --> 00:13:37.770
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Well,
and I'm from Cleveland.

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:39.690
So when the death of
Superman happened,

00:13:39.690 --> 00:13:43.110
I was actually working at a
comic book store in Cleveland,

00:13:43.110 --> 00:13:44.370
going to art school.

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:47.220
And the line out the door that
day that Superman died was--

00:13:47.220 --> 00:13:48.470
DAN JURGENS: Oh, it was crazy.

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:49.290
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
--the craziest thing

00:13:49.290 --> 00:13:50.280
I'd ever experienced.

00:13:50.280 --> 00:13:53.190
We were in a mall in
downtown Cleveland.

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:55.770
And it was the length
of the mall of people

00:13:55.770 --> 00:13:57.479
just buying Superman comics.

00:13:57.479 --> 00:13:59.520
And the whole point of
working at the comic store

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:00.995
was not have to work this hard.

00:14:00.995 --> 00:14:02.699
So I was very annoyed by you.

00:14:02.699 --> 00:14:04.740
I wanted to sit and draw
my pages at the counter.

00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:05.910
DAN JURGENS: I apologize now.

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:07.600
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
And then I remember being

00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:08.910
completely flustered by this.

00:14:08.910 --> 00:14:09.930
And the phone rang.

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:11.670
And it was my mother.

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:13.549
And she goes, is
Superman really dead?

00:14:13.549 --> 00:14:14.340
And I just hung up.

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:15.270
Uh, I've got to go.

00:14:15.270 --> 00:14:16.936
And it was a crazy day.

00:14:16.936 --> 00:14:19.560
SPEAKER 1: It was the first time
that had ever happened, right?

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:21.101
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
No, yeah, yeah.

00:14:21.101 --> 00:14:24.750
I have a very definitive
memory of everyone

00:14:24.750 --> 00:14:27.050
really believing this
was going to happen.

00:14:27.050 --> 00:14:28.300
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, now
they come back to life.

00:14:28.300 --> 00:14:28.750
But--

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:30.125
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Yeah, but--

00:14:30.125 --> 00:14:31.710
SPEAKER 1: --not
back in the day.

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:32.670
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
They fell for it.

00:14:32.670 --> 00:14:33.240
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, exactly.

00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:35.115
DAN JURGENS: Well,
although-- and I've always

00:14:35.115 --> 00:14:38.280
said, at the time, we did
not know when and how we

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:39.570
were going to bring him back.

00:14:39.570 --> 00:14:42.840
We knew inevitably it
would happen at some point.

00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:44.797
But then we also
suspended publication

00:14:44.797 --> 00:14:46.380
for a couple of
months and everything.

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:47.610
And we did not know.

00:14:47.610 --> 00:14:49.110
When we did that
entire story, we

00:14:49.110 --> 00:14:51.640
had no idea how it
was going to happen.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:54.570
We didn't know when exactly
it was going to happen,

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:57.390
just that eventually
it obviously had to.

00:14:57.390 --> 00:14:58.980
But we didn't know.

00:14:58.980 --> 00:15:00.420
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: No, but
you did the perfect thing.

00:15:00.420 --> 00:15:01.630
It was never about the death.

00:15:01.630 --> 00:15:02.670
It was what do
you get out of it?

00:15:02.670 --> 00:15:03.550
DAN JURGENS: Right, exactly.

00:15:03.550 --> 00:15:05.383
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
And that's the mistake

00:15:05.383 --> 00:15:08.280
when you see other people
doing their death-cycle story,

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:10.680
they're so obsessed
with selling the death

00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:13.140
that it's really what
do you get out of it?

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:15.940
Like, what kind of new stories
are you going to get like--

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:18.720
any superhero, it's
like, Batman dies.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:22.320
And then you get all the other
players rise to the occasion.

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:23.610
And you get a new story.

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:25.290
And that's what you
guys had for years.

00:15:25.290 --> 00:15:27.780
DAN JURGENS: Yeah, yeah, we did.

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:30.630
SPEAKER 1: So, Brian,
how did you end up at DC?

00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:33.810
And why did you want to write
Action Comics and Superman?

00:15:33.810 --> 00:15:36.030
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
I ended up at DC--

00:15:36.030 --> 00:15:38.040
over the years, they
had been very kind

00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:40.290
and made it clear
that I was invited.

00:15:40.290 --> 00:15:44.480
And a few years ago, a
serious offer was made.

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:46.695
But it just wasn't time yet.

00:15:46.695 --> 00:15:48.560
I knew it would
happen eventually.

00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:51.690
I just, I knew me well enough
to know, boy, it was just--

00:15:51.690 --> 00:15:53.340
but it wasn't time.

00:15:53.340 --> 00:15:56.070
I didn't feel like I'd finished
what I was doing over there

00:15:56.070 --> 00:15:58.480
with "Jessica Jones" and
Miles and some other stuff.

00:15:58.480 --> 00:16:02.700
But this time around,
they came at me

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:06.600
with a really decent offer that
was worth turning to my friends

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:08.190
at Marvel, who I
was friends with--

00:16:08.190 --> 00:16:09.709
I'm still friends with.

00:16:09.709 --> 00:16:11.250
And to turn to them
and go, hey, I've

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:13.890
got to go, it's got to be
enough for them to go, yeah,

00:16:13.890 --> 00:16:14.790
you've got to go.

00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:17.070
It had to be enough
for them to agree.

00:16:17.070 --> 00:16:19.960
And it was.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:24.224
And, yeah, I think
Dan and Jim just--

00:16:24.224 --> 00:16:25.890
I guess everyone walks
in there and says

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:26.848
they want to do Batman.

00:16:26.848 --> 00:16:28.860
I guess that's
what everyone does.

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:31.410
And so they were
braced for that and how

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:33.450
they were going to tell
me I'm not doing Batman.

00:16:33.450 --> 00:16:38.700
But I said, if it comes
along that Superman

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:43.266
becomes available, that would
be, I think, where I would go.

00:16:43.266 --> 00:16:44.640
But I don't know
where you're at.

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:46.350
And, again, it's someone's gig.

00:16:46.350 --> 00:16:48.280
I don't want to
take someone's gig.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:52.500
And then a day later,
he got over the shock

00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:58.050
of me saying Superman and
said, actually, Action #1000

00:16:58.050 --> 00:16:59.064
is coming down--

00:16:59.064 --> 00:17:00.480
like, I don't want
to rush things.

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:03.160
But, boy, there's a
real opportunity here.

00:17:03.160 --> 00:17:05.520
And I go, all right,
let me think about it.

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:07.859
And then I went
back to Cleveland

00:17:07.859 --> 00:17:09.005
for my brother's wedding.

00:17:09.005 --> 00:17:11.130
It just so happened my
brother was getting married.

00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:13.223
And sorry you have to
hear this again, Dan.

00:17:13.223 --> 00:17:13.722
And--

00:17:13.722 --> 00:17:15.810
DAN JURGENS: No problem.

00:17:15.810 --> 00:17:17.670
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
And at the library

00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:21.030
I used to hang out in all
the time, one of my friends

00:17:21.030 --> 00:17:21.910
helps run it now.

00:17:21.910 --> 00:17:24.880
And he had put together
a Superman exhibit

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:28.950
at the Cleveland Museum that
connected Cleveland and Judaism

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:32.820
and Superman and me and all this
other-- and I walk in there.

00:17:32.820 --> 00:17:35.220
And it was like this maze
I had to walk through.

00:17:35.220 --> 00:17:37.830
And by the end of it,
I just texted my wife

00:17:37.830 --> 00:17:38.960
and go, close the deal.

00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:40.400
I have to do this.

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:43.800
It really felt like someone
had put a show on for me.

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:46.350
It's like, see, you
love all this stuff.

00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:47.570
You're connected to it.

00:17:47.570 --> 00:17:50.160
It's part of your DNA.

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:51.330
And I just flashed.

00:17:51.330 --> 00:17:53.880
I remembered I was the
artist for the Superman

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:55.710
parade in the '80s
when I was in college,

00:17:55.710 --> 00:17:57.960
and how connected
it was to my youth.

00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:00.540
And, boom, here we are.

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:01.410
SPEAKER 1: Great.

00:18:01.410 --> 00:18:06.870
So you brought up Action Comics
#1000 which is why we're here.

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:09.960
So, Marv, you have a story
coming up in Action Comics

00:18:09.960 --> 00:18:12.829
#1000 using artwork from
the legendary Curt Swan.

00:18:12.829 --> 00:18:13.620
MARV WOLFMAN: Yeah.

00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:15.960
SPEAKER 1: And what was
it like to script a story

00:18:15.960 --> 00:18:17.760
drawn by such an
acclaimed artist that's

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:18.510
no longer with us?

00:18:18.510 --> 00:18:19.968
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: And where was

00:18:19.968 --> 00:18:21.220
this art for all these years?

00:18:21.220 --> 00:18:23.140
MARV WOLFMAN: I don't know.

00:18:23.140 --> 00:18:27.950
There were four pages that
they found of something.

00:18:27.950 --> 00:18:30.100
Superman's not in it.

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:31.380
They're a fragment.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:32.650
It's not the first page.

00:18:32.650 --> 00:18:34.395
There is no last page.

00:18:34.395 --> 00:18:36.060
It was dialogued.

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:39.754
I have a hunch it was a writing
test of just four pages given

00:18:39.754 --> 00:18:40.920
out to writers of something.

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:41.628
But I don't know.

00:18:41.628 --> 00:18:43.950
Of course, nobody up there
is aware of what it is.

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:47.940
My assignment was to strip
out the copy, look at it,

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:50.290
and turn it into a complete
story with a beginning,

00:18:50.290 --> 00:18:52.706
middle, and end, even though
there's no beginning, middle,

00:18:52.706 --> 00:18:55.770
and end, and to make
it a Superman story,

00:18:55.770 --> 00:18:57.990
even though there's
no Superman in it,

00:18:57.990 --> 00:19:02.010
and to create an entire thing.

00:19:02.010 --> 00:19:05.880
And I used to do this all the
time as an assistant editor

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:06.780
to Joe Kubert.

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:09.196
We would take old stories--

00:19:09.196 --> 00:19:11.070
I don't know why Joe
wanted it done this way.

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:13.530
But we'd take old war stories.

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:17.970
And I would rewrite them
as current unknown soldier

00:19:17.970 --> 00:19:19.350
stories.

00:19:19.350 --> 00:19:21.030
At Marvel, we did it once.

00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:24.690
And I don't remember the
order, but we lost the license

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:30.840
to either "John Carter"
or "Planet of the Apes."

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:33.150
We had the artwork for
one of those books,

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:35.760
and it had to be
converted to the other.

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:37.500
How you take a
"John Carter" story

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:39.916
and turn it into a "Planet of
the Apes," I don't remember.

00:19:39.916 --> 00:19:41.670
But anyway, it's a
great, fun thing.

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:43.540
Now, I had worked
a lot with Kurt.

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:45.840
I did Superman for
years with Kurt.

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:47.177
Kurt is wonderful.

00:19:47.177 --> 00:19:48.510
I mean, he's a brilliant artist.

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:50.380
I just loved his stuff.

00:19:50.380 --> 00:19:55.030
So the idea of being able to
take these four isolated pages

00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:58.480
and turn it into a
complete Superman story--

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:00.250
and I threw in a
Superman villain,

00:20:00.250 --> 00:20:04.540
who you also don't see, because
the pages were already drawn--

00:20:04.540 --> 00:20:05.620
was just wonderful.

00:20:05.620 --> 00:20:08.170
It was like working
with Kurt again.

00:20:08.170 --> 00:20:10.120
He was a dear, sweet man.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:11.620
When I was at
Disney, I would hire

00:20:11.620 --> 00:20:14.950
him to do short stories for us.

00:20:14.950 --> 00:20:17.530
He was one of those
people I grew up with.

00:20:17.530 --> 00:20:22.180
And I always wondered why
the covers of "Jimmy Olsen"

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:24.130
and a couple of the
books were so much better

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:25.340
than the insides.

00:20:25.340 --> 00:20:28.210
And then I discovered all
the covers were done by Kurt.

00:20:28.210 --> 00:20:31.900
Great artist, and it was
so much fun to do it.

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:33.480
SPEAKER 1: That's awesome.

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:36.680
So, Paul, I wanted to
ask about "Superman"

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:39.900
the animated series, because it
seems like for a lot of fans,

00:20:39.900 --> 00:20:42.872
he's the definitive
version of Superman.

00:20:42.872 --> 00:20:45.330
So what do you think makes him
distinct from other versions

00:20:45.330 --> 00:20:46.820
of the Man of Steel?

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:48.570
PAUL DINI: Well, with
the animated series,

00:20:48.570 --> 00:20:53.100
we were lucky in that we had
such an incredible wealth

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:57.930
and history of material to
draw from, from Superman's

00:20:57.930 --> 00:21:02.100
various incarnations, from
comic books, from radio shows,

00:21:02.100 --> 00:21:02.940
from comic strips.

00:21:02.940 --> 00:21:07.170
Everything that he is in the
public mind we distilled down

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:14.110
into what we felt was a
universal telling of his story.

00:21:14.110 --> 00:21:19.080
And we were able to concentrate
on him as Superman and Clark

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:26.760
Kent and also expand his cast
so it included the Kents back

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:29.310
at the farm, and
Lois, and Jimmy,

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:30.670
and do a take on all of them.

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:33.780
So it really grew beyond
Superman to being a show

00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:36.780
that you really enjoyed
all his characters and all

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:38.460
the extended cast.

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:40.260
And it was fun to--

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:43.740
I know there have been
other animated versions.

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:45.820
And those characters were
certainly a part of it.

00:21:45.820 --> 00:21:50.160
But in this case, we were really
able to draw from the work that

00:21:50.160 --> 00:21:57.010
had gone before and make
Lois and Darkseid and Lana,

00:21:57.010 --> 00:22:01.350
fun versions that, I think, were
unique to the animated series

00:22:01.350 --> 00:22:05.070
but also rang true to
the fans in general.

00:22:05.070 --> 00:22:07.690
And also, Superman
himself was just--

00:22:07.690 --> 00:22:08.620
he was a joy to write.

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:09.810
At first, I was
wondering, how am I

00:22:09.810 --> 00:22:11.280
going to write this character?

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:13.860
Because he doesn't
have the moodiness

00:22:13.860 --> 00:22:15.210
and the dark side of Batman.

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:18.810
But he is an incredibly
likable character,

00:22:18.810 --> 00:22:21.310
both as Clark and as Superman.

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:26.040
And it's fun, perhaps,
making him maybe

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:28.530
a little lower on the power
scale than he was in the comics

00:22:28.530 --> 00:22:31.780
so that he was able to wrestle
with things a little bit more.

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:36.090
So it was more of a
matter of mind over matter

00:22:36.090 --> 00:22:38.370
than just brawn, even though
you can show everything

00:22:38.370 --> 00:22:39.390
in a cartoon.

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:41.760
He was a challenge to write,
and it was a lot of fun.

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:44.162
And I think people
picked up on that fun.

00:22:44.162 --> 00:22:45.620
SPEAKER 1: So now
I want to move on

00:22:45.620 --> 00:22:50.310
to my favorite part of the
talk, which is villains.

00:22:50.310 --> 00:22:53.070
What do you think are or what
do you think are the most

00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:56.022
interesting Superman villains?

00:22:56.022 --> 00:22:57.980
And we have the
obvious, obviously.

00:22:57.980 --> 00:22:59.370
But-- Lex.

00:22:59.370 --> 00:23:00.960
[CHUCKLES] That's my favorite.

00:23:00.960 --> 00:23:03.330
DAN JURGENS: Yeah,
I like Lex a lot.

00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:08.190
I mean, I could do a three-year
Lex Luthor series easily.

00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:09.870
I think there is that.

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:13.400
I was also always intrigued by
Toyman, for whatever reason,

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:17.670
just because it was so counter
to who Superman is, right?

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:19.290
I mean, here's this guy--

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:21.090
and that was always a
problem Superman had,

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:22.260
which was villains.

00:23:22.260 --> 00:23:24.652
I mean, if you look throughout
the history of Superman,

00:23:24.652 --> 00:23:26.860
there was always a problem
with some of the villains.

00:23:26.860 --> 00:23:29.610
But I found Toyman to
be strangely intriguing,

00:23:29.610 --> 00:23:33.000
just because he was so different
than Superman, which was here's

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:34.270
a guy who makes toys.

00:23:34.270 --> 00:23:37.740
How can he possibly be
a threat to Superman?

00:23:37.740 --> 00:23:40.470
How does that story not
end on page one, right?

00:23:40.470 --> 00:23:41.640
Superman shows up.

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:42.790
Boom, you're gone.

00:23:42.790 --> 00:23:44.640
The story is over.

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:47.760
So I was always intrigued
by that level of villain

00:23:47.760 --> 00:23:51.045
and how you could possibly
make it work with Superman.

00:23:51.045 --> 00:23:52.670
SPEAKER 1: I didn't
expect that answer.

00:23:52.670 --> 00:23:53.100
Thank you.

00:23:53.100 --> 00:23:53.440
That's great.

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:53.610
DAN JURGENS: Sure.

00:23:53.610 --> 00:23:54.460
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Yeah, Toyman

00:23:54.460 --> 00:23:55.804
shows up in my second issue.

00:23:55.804 --> 00:23:56.720
I couldn't believe it.

00:23:56.720 --> 00:23:56.920
DAN JURGENS: See, you get it.

00:23:56.920 --> 00:23:57.500
You get it, yeah.

00:23:57.500 --> 00:23:58.825
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: But I
couldn't believe it, either.

00:23:58.825 --> 00:23:59.741
I couldn't believe it.

00:23:59.741 --> 00:24:03.370
I go, my subconscious put it in.

00:24:03.370 --> 00:24:05.604
And as I'm consciously
writing it, I go--

00:24:05.604 --> 00:24:06.270
DAN JURGENS: OK.

00:24:06.270 --> 00:24:06.840
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
--it must happen.

00:24:06.840 --> 00:24:07.500
We agree.

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:07.730
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:24:07.730 --> 00:24:08.972
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:24:08.972 --> 00:24:09.930
SPEAKER 1: Anyone else?

00:24:09.930 --> 00:24:13.050
PAUL DINI: I always liked the--

00:24:13.050 --> 00:24:15.630
with Lex Luthor,
there was something

00:24:15.630 --> 00:24:18.600
I always found rather poignant
with their relationship

00:24:18.600 --> 00:24:24.090
in thinking about the character,
in that Lex is someone who has

00:24:24.090 --> 00:24:26.580
basically had to buy affection.

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:30.090
Like, he put himself on
the scale in Metropolis,

00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:32.160
where he is beneficence.

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:38.310
And he has created all these
great scientific advances.

00:24:38.310 --> 00:24:41.310
And I'm sure his name is on
a lot of public buildings.

00:24:41.310 --> 00:24:44.100
And I'm sure he is
lauded wherever he goes.

00:24:44.100 --> 00:24:47.820
But that wouldn't happen unless
he was paying for it, unless he

00:24:47.820 --> 00:24:51.030
was going out there and
buying affection, as it was,

00:24:51.030 --> 00:24:54.175
with his inventions and
with the things he does.

00:24:54.175 --> 00:24:56.550
And there is Superman, who
just does it out of his heart.

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:58.590
And people flock to him.

00:24:58.590 --> 00:25:03.570
And I think that galls Luthor
on a deeply soulful level.

00:25:03.570 --> 00:25:05.940
And it's like, I have
to do all this just

00:25:05.940 --> 00:25:07.860
to get a friendly hello.

00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:10.680
And he rescues a cat out of
a tree, and I'm forgotten.

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:13.710
And I think that, in a lot
of ways, spurs on his hatred.

00:25:16.602 --> 00:25:18.060
MARV WOLFMAN: I
like the characters

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:19.630
who can out-think Superman.

00:25:19.630 --> 00:25:23.237
I'm not really into
the big punchy guys

00:25:23.237 --> 00:25:25.320
because you're not going
to be able to defeat him.

00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:29.850
The beauty of what you did was
that he was finally meeting

00:25:29.850 --> 00:25:31.480
a character who could do that.

00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:34.410
But in the past, if Luthor
put on a super suit,

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:35.834
or somebody else
attacked him, he

00:25:35.834 --> 00:25:37.250
could physically
take care of you.

00:25:37.250 --> 00:25:38.790
So that's not interesting.

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:42.870
What I like is the characters
who out-think because that's

00:25:42.870 --> 00:25:44.700
not Superman's superpower.

00:25:44.700 --> 00:25:46.830
He's smart, but he's not Luthor.

00:25:46.830 --> 00:25:49.920
He's not Brainiac.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:53.160
And those characters, to
me, are far more interesting

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:55.290
because they match
Superman in ways

00:25:55.290 --> 00:26:00.730
that Superman doesn't
deal with the best.

00:26:00.730 --> 00:26:04.440
He has to go out of his
way and find some way

00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:07.770
to deal with them that's
not in his comfort zone.

00:26:07.770 --> 00:26:13.585
So to me, Brainiac and Luthor
are the strongest characters.

00:26:13.585 --> 00:26:14.960
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: And we have

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:16.780
some new villains coming up.

00:26:16.780 --> 00:26:19.790
Starting in Action
#1000, it's the debut

00:26:19.790 --> 00:26:22.760
of a big new villain
for Superman,

00:26:22.760 --> 00:26:25.220
because I agree with Dan.

00:26:25.220 --> 00:26:29.480
As good as the good villains
are, there are good villains.

00:26:29.480 --> 00:26:31.500
And then there are some others.

00:26:31.500 --> 00:26:32.960
But it's not enough.

00:26:32.960 --> 00:26:35.420
Compared to, like,
Spider-Man or Batman,

00:26:35.420 --> 00:26:38.150
he doesn't have nearly the
rogues gallery that he should

00:26:38.150 --> 00:26:40.760
have, compared to his legacy.

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:43.310
So we're going to be as
additive as possible.

00:26:43.310 --> 00:26:45.510
And starting right
away with Action

00:26:45.510 --> 00:26:50.660
#1000 is this new villain who
knows something about Superman

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:54.440
and the history of Superman
that Superman does not know.

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:59.030
And that's going to really
challenge him, both spiritually

00:26:59.030 --> 00:27:00.230
and physically.

00:27:00.230 --> 00:27:03.050
And then in the pages
of Action Comics,

00:27:03.050 --> 00:27:07.670
we're debuting some criminal
activity in Metropolis

00:27:07.670 --> 00:27:10.190
that has been going on
right under Superman's nose.

00:27:10.190 --> 00:27:13.340
There is a criminal
who has no ego.

00:27:13.340 --> 00:27:15.530
Like, Lex has a lot of ego.

00:27:15.530 --> 00:27:19.740
I need Superman to acknowledge
that I did this, you know?

00:27:19.740 --> 00:27:24.710
And imagine a criminal that
is inspired by Lex Luthor

00:27:24.710 --> 00:27:28.760
and excited by, yeah, Lex, you
go get Superman's attention

00:27:28.760 --> 00:27:29.750
as much as you want.

00:27:29.750 --> 00:27:31.250
Go get Daddy's attention.

00:27:31.250 --> 00:27:33.740
And we're going to run
our business like adults.

00:27:33.740 --> 00:27:35.390
And I don't need
Superman's attention.

00:27:35.390 --> 00:27:36.770
And I don't need any of it.

00:27:36.770 --> 00:27:39.110
And what kind of criminal
empire can you build right

00:27:39.110 --> 00:27:40.370
under Superman's nose?

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:43.894
How smart do you have
to be to do this,

00:27:43.894 --> 00:27:46.310
and it's been going on for
years, and he didn't even know?

00:27:46.310 --> 00:27:49.435
So that's what we're going to
be doing coming in the future.

00:27:49.435 --> 00:27:50.060
SPEAKER 1: Wow.

00:27:50.060 --> 00:27:50.810
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:52.650
SPEAKER 1: So you've
got to pick that up.

00:27:52.650 --> 00:27:53.420
So no names?

00:27:53.420 --> 00:27:54.810
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: That was
my point, if I wasn't clear.

00:27:54.810 --> 00:27:55.690
[CHUCKLING]

00:27:55.690 --> 00:27:56.570
PAUL DINI: Yeah.

00:27:56.570 --> 00:27:58.610
SPEAKER 1: Trying to
sell comics here, guys.

00:27:58.610 --> 00:27:59.600
So no names?

00:27:59.600 --> 00:28:01.040
You can't spoil the name yet?

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:02.540
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Well, the name

00:28:02.540 --> 00:28:06.320
of the big villain in Action
#1000 is named Rogol Zar.

00:28:06.320 --> 00:28:12.110
And this is an alien that's
coming to Earth with an agenda.

00:28:12.110 --> 00:28:15.110
The first part of the name
is named after my doctor,

00:28:15.110 --> 00:28:16.320
who saved my life.

00:28:16.320 --> 00:28:19.250
I had a big thing last December.

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:20.720
I had a MRSA infection.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:22.520
And every day, I would hear her.

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:24.892
This German woman would
come in and work on my face.

00:28:24.892 --> 00:28:25.850
But I couldn't see her.

00:28:25.850 --> 00:28:26.660
I was blind.

00:28:26.660 --> 00:28:28.640
And I'd hear this
name, Rogol, every day.

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:30.014
And then I'd go,
she's definitely

00:28:30.014 --> 00:28:31.490
going to be the villain.

00:28:31.490 --> 00:28:33.860
And I couldn't wait to
tell her as soon as I--

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:36.082
and then I told her when
I was finally awake.

00:28:36.082 --> 00:28:38.540
And I go, I think I'm going to
use your name as the villain

00:28:38.540 --> 00:28:40.100
in the new Superman books.

00:28:40.100 --> 00:28:41.240
And she went, uh-huh.

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:44.773
And then I realized I never told
her what I did for a living.

00:28:44.773 --> 00:28:47.020
Like, and so it just sounded
like an insane person.

00:28:47.020 --> 00:28:49.070
And then she Googled me
and then the next day

00:28:49.070 --> 00:28:52.319
came in very excited
that she may actually

00:28:52.319 --> 00:28:53.360
be in the Superman books.

00:28:53.360 --> 00:28:55.070
DAN JURGENS: And
can I just say how

00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:57.500
cool it is you work
in a Google plug?

00:28:57.500 --> 00:28:57.770
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: I did.

00:28:57.770 --> 00:28:58.370
DAN JURGENS: Yeah, you did.

00:28:58.370 --> 00:28:59.560
PAUL DINI: Yeah, you
definitely did that.

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:00.610
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Do
I get free Google now?

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:01.360
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:01.860
[CHUCKLING]

