SPEAKER 1: I didn't know that.

00:29:03.110 --> 00:29:04.370
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:29:04.370 --> 00:29:05.510
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:09.560
OK, so do you guys prefer
to think about Superman

00:29:09.560 --> 00:29:12.320
as the last survivor
of Krypton or as part

00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:13.940
of an extended
family of survivors

00:29:13.940 --> 00:29:18.464
that includes Zod, Supergirl,
his dog Krypto, et cetera?

00:29:18.464 --> 00:29:19.880
DAN JURGENS:
Somewhere in between.

00:29:19.880 --> 00:29:20.760
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:24.770
DAN JURGENS: I think that
one of the nicest titles that

00:29:24.770 --> 00:29:27.260
can be ascribed to Superman
is last son of Krypton.

00:29:27.260 --> 00:29:29.925
I just love that because it
is so heavy with implication.

00:29:29.925 --> 00:29:31.550
MARV WOLFMAN: Yeah,
the responsibility.

00:29:31.550 --> 00:29:33.610
DAN JURGENS: Right, exactly.

00:29:33.610 --> 00:29:37.340
It describes him and his
background so well, just

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:38.840
last son of Krypton.

00:29:38.840 --> 00:29:40.760
And so I really like that.

00:29:40.760 --> 00:29:42.860
And it's like, OK,
Supergirl, fine.

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:44.450
But there comes a
point where it gets

00:29:44.450 --> 00:29:47.390
kind of too much because
then that invalidates

00:29:47.390 --> 00:29:49.140
the last son of Krypton idea.

00:29:49.140 --> 00:29:52.220
So I say it's like in the
middle somewhere, little more

00:29:52.220 --> 00:29:53.600
towards just a handful.

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:57.520
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: What would
