00:30:16.150 --> 00:30:17.510
SPEAKER 1: There's a couple
of people here, they're like--

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:19.160
true nerds are
like, you got to--

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:21.820
OK, so, Paul, in "Superman--

00:30:21.820 --> 00:30:24.670
Peace on Earth," Superman
confronts the limits of his

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:28.360
powers, not in the form of
an all-powerful super villain

00:30:28.360 --> 00:30:31.870
but against a very
real problem--

00:30:31.870 --> 00:30:32.830
world hunger.

00:30:32.830 --> 00:30:35.620
Why did you choose to
test Superman this way?

00:30:35.620 --> 00:30:38.320
PAUL DINI: Well, when
Alex Ross and I came up

00:30:38.320 --> 00:30:40.930
with a story for that,
we wanted to tell

00:30:40.930 --> 00:30:43.210
a story that was very
close to Superman's heart

00:30:43.210 --> 00:30:44.560
and also to his origins.

00:30:44.560 --> 00:30:48.490
We didn't really want to do
the ultimate punch-up with Lex

00:30:48.490 --> 00:30:50.200
or Brainiac or
anything like that.

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:54.820
We wanted to go back to Superman
at his most human level,

00:30:54.820 --> 00:30:58.480
and also do a story that speaks
to his origin as a farmer

00:30:58.480 --> 00:31:01.600
because he goes back
to that at the end,

00:31:01.600 --> 00:31:06.520
at least as a touchstone
at the end of that story.

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:09.190
But it was also kind
of we put ourselves

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:11.830
in the position of what
if we were Superman?

00:31:11.830 --> 00:31:13.270
I think everybody
has fantasized,

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:14.353
I want to put on the cape.

00:31:14.353 --> 00:31:18.590
And I want to solve all
of humanity's problems.

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:20.900
And once we looked at it
from that point of view,

00:31:20.900 --> 00:31:24.100
it was like, OK, then we're
dealing in a real world,

00:31:24.100 --> 00:31:26.230
with real people, with
other countries that

00:31:26.230 --> 00:31:28.270
have other agendas.

00:31:28.270 --> 00:31:32.750
And the ideals of Superman don't
always work in the real world.

00:31:32.750 --> 00:31:37.270
I mean, it gets to be
too human, too selfish.

00:31:37.270 --> 00:31:40.370
And what does he do in
a situation like that?

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:42.520
If he goes out to
eliminate that,

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:46.930
then he becomes a god, a
monster, or a dictator.

00:31:46.930 --> 00:31:49.300
And he's got to
take a step back.

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:52.840
And even though what he's trying
to do is set a good example

00:31:52.840 --> 00:31:55.700
and be altruistic, all
he can do is suggest.

00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:57.790
And all he can do is
lead in small ways.

00:31:57.790 --> 00:31:59.890
He can't solve the big problems.

00:31:59.890 --> 00:32:02.560
When a dam is busting or when
aliens invade, that's great.

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:06.880
But on a real human level, when
it comes to give and receive,

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:08.590
he's just as human as all of us.

00:32:08.590 --> 00:32:12.940
And that was something
that was really important

00:32:12.940 --> 00:32:14.742
for us to touch on that.

00:32:14.742 --> 00:32:16.470
SPEAKER 1: That's great.

00:32:16.470 --> 00:32:20.240
Marv, I heard you got
lucky as a young man

00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:22.510
while touring the DC
office and received

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:24.880
an unpublished Superman story.

00:32:24.880 --> 00:32:26.170
Can you talk about that?

00:32:26.170 --> 00:32:27.670
And is it true that
it's about to be

00:32:27.670 --> 00:32:29.800
published for the first
time in "Action Comics--

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:31.370
80 Years of Superman"?

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:33.850
MARV WOLFMAN:
Yeah, the DC Comics

00:32:33.850 --> 00:32:38.440
used to have a tour every
week of the DC offices.

00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:40.505
And I went to high
school about four

00:32:40.505 --> 00:32:42.630
or five blocks away-- high
school of art and design

00:32:42.630 --> 00:32:45.460
because my intent was
to become an artist.

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:47.720
So I would run over
there and go on the tours

00:32:47.720 --> 00:32:48.610
when I was able to.

00:32:51.140 --> 00:32:52.550
One of the times
that I was going

00:32:52.550 --> 00:32:57.050
there, Sol Harrison, who was the
production chief at the time--

00:32:57.050 --> 00:33:02.650
later became publisher-- was
wheeling out a post-office

00:33:02.650 --> 00:33:03.350
cart--

00:33:03.350 --> 00:33:05.050
one of these things
that's about--

00:33:05.050 --> 00:33:10.370
oops-- six, seven feet
wide, six, seven feet long,

00:33:10.370 --> 00:33:14.690
four feet wide, four feet
high, filled with artwork

00:33:14.690 --> 00:33:18.080
from the 1940s, all of
which was being written off.

00:33:18.080 --> 00:33:19.760
It was never published.

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:22.100
And they were finally
trying to clear space.

00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:24.317
And he was taking it
to the incinerators.

00:33:24.317 --> 00:33:25.400
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Ugh.

00:33:25.400 --> 00:33:26.025
SPEAKER 1: Ugh.

00:33:26.025 --> 00:33:28.874
MARV WOLFMAN: Now, you've got
to remember, it's horrifying,

00:33:28.874 --> 00:33:31.040
even the concept of that
and some of the other stuff

00:33:31.040 --> 00:33:32.000
that was done.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:36.480
But back then, not even the
artist wanted their art back.

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:38.640
To most of those people,
most of the artists--

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:40.170
because I've spoken to them--

00:33:40.170 --> 00:33:43.190
they wanted to
clear their offices.

00:33:43.190 --> 00:33:46.732
It was giant stacks of paper
that had no value, as far

00:33:46.732 --> 00:33:47.690
as they were concerned.

00:33:47.690 --> 00:33:51.130
It took the fans-- it
took those of us here

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:54.590
and the fans from my generation
to say this work had value.

00:33:54.590 --> 00:33:55.810
This work was special.

00:33:55.810 --> 00:33:57.620
Anyway, he's wheeling
this stuff out.

00:33:57.620 --> 00:34:00.620
And there's three or
four people on the tour.

00:34:00.620 --> 00:34:02.480
And he says, if you
kids want anything,

00:34:02.480 --> 00:34:05.540
grab it before I take
it to the incinerator.

00:34:05.540 --> 00:34:11.300
Like Uncle Scrooge, we dove
into the money vault, swam

00:34:11.300 --> 00:34:14.480
through the pages, grabbed
everything we could.

00:34:14.480 --> 00:34:16.190
Did not take the
rest of the tour

00:34:16.190 --> 00:34:18.290
because we were weighed
down with artwork.

00:34:18.290 --> 00:34:20.389
And this is the 1940s artwork.

00:34:20.389 --> 00:34:23.690
So it's a lot larger than
the artwork that most of you

00:34:23.690 --> 00:34:27.530
may be familiar with that
you see at conventions.

00:34:27.530 --> 00:34:30.460
We rushed downstairs
and started trading.

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:34.370
And I noticed that
I had 8 or 9 pages

00:34:34.370 --> 00:34:38.239
of a 12-page story that was all
written off a Superman story.

00:34:38.239 --> 00:34:43.580
And I started trading multiple
pages to get the last three.

00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:45.420
So I walked out of there.

00:34:45.420 --> 00:34:49.370
I took a cab at,
like, 13 years old.

00:34:49.370 --> 00:34:52.699
I had to get a cab--
because it was so heavy--

00:34:52.699 --> 00:34:54.980
with a complete Superman
story, as well as

00:34:54.980 --> 00:34:56.630
a whole bunch of other stuff.

00:34:56.630 --> 00:35:00.400
And it never saw print.

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:01.820
It never had.

00:35:01.820 --> 00:35:05.510
When they were putting
together the "Action Comics--

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:10.367
80 Years of Superman"
Deluxe Edition, Paul Levitz,

00:35:10.367 --> 00:35:12.950
who used to be publisher-- he's
now working with them in other

00:35:12.950 --> 00:35:14.120
ways--

00:35:14.120 --> 00:35:16.430
asked if he could print it.

00:35:16.430 --> 00:35:17.600
And I said, absolutely.

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:19.040
This is the perfect place.

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:22.442
It's the only place that
I would have said yes to.

00:35:22.442 --> 00:35:23.650
And you'll be able to see it.

00:35:23.650 --> 00:35:26.510
They left it in black and white
because it was never published.

00:35:26.510 --> 00:35:27.770
It was never colored.

00:35:27.770 --> 00:35:29.660
And they didn't want
to color it now.

00:35:29.660 --> 00:35:31.576
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Why wasn't it published?

00:35:31.576 --> 00:35:32.420
Do you know why?

00:35:32.420 --> 00:35:36.600
MARV WOLFMAN: They had thousands
of pages of unpublished stuff.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:43.280
Now, the artwork was done in
1946, written by Jerry Siegel,

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:45.410
drawn by the Joe
Shuster Studios.

00:35:45.410 --> 00:35:49.460
That we know because Paul Levitz
was able to find the bills.

00:35:49.460 --> 00:35:51.070
DC has everything.

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:55.450
But they found that.

00:35:55.450 --> 00:35:57.500
Why it wasn't published
back then, I don't know.

00:35:57.500 --> 00:35:58.257
But it never was.

00:35:58.257 --> 00:36:00.590
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Was it,
like, filthy or something?

00:36:00.590 --> 00:36:01.045
MARV WOLFMAN: No.

00:36:01.045 --> 00:36:03.545
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: It was
like a completely inappropriate

00:36:03.545 --> 00:36:04.580
Superman.

00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:07.730
MARV WOLFMAN: It was as weird
as all the stories from 1940s

00:36:07.730 --> 00:36:08.360
were.

00:36:08.360 --> 00:36:14.970
But two years later,
in 1947 or '48,

00:36:14.970 --> 00:36:18.630
we found a new version of
that story, drawn by Wayne

00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:21.120
Boring, now a 10-page story.

00:36:21.120 --> 00:36:23.740
So for some reason, they
decided not to publish it

00:36:23.740 --> 00:36:26.940
but then reused the script,
only cleaning it up or fixing it

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:27.990
up a little bit better.

00:36:27.990 --> 00:36:28.560
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Fascinating.

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:30.480
MARV WOLFMAN: So for
the first time ever,

00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:31.920
the story is going to see print.

00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:34.810
And it couldn't be in a
better book than that one.

00:36:34.810 --> 00:36:36.230
So I'm really pleased about it.

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:36.635
PAUL DINI: Right.

00:36:36.635 --> 00:36:37.635
SPEAKER 1: That's great.

00:36:37.635 --> 00:36:38.960
I'm jealous.

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:41.610
So we're, unfortunately,
almost running out of time,

00:36:41.610 --> 00:36:43.930
and we want to get some
audience questions going.

00:36:43.930 --> 00:36:45.990
So as a last quick
general question,

00:36:45.990 --> 00:36:48.930
what are your favorite
Superman stories?

00:36:48.930 --> 00:36:49.930
It can be one you wrote.

00:36:55.800 --> 00:36:58.300
DAN JURGENS: I am really bad
at issue numbers and everything

00:36:58.300 --> 00:36:58.799
else.

00:36:58.799 --> 00:37:02.230
But there is a story that--
we had earlier mentioned Wayne

00:37:02.230 --> 00:37:03.160
Boring--

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:05.190
where Superman goes
back to Krypton.

00:37:05.190 --> 00:37:07.482
And it must've been
a late-'50s story.

00:37:07.482 --> 00:37:08.440
Help me out here, Marv.

00:37:08.440 --> 00:37:09.220
MARV WOLFMAN: Yes, it is.

00:37:09.220 --> 00:37:09.370
DAN JURGENS: You know
what the story is.

00:37:09.370 --> 00:37:10.390
Yeah, "Superman's
Return to Krypton"

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:11.260
was the title of the story.

00:37:11.260 --> 00:37:12.593
MARV WOLFMAN: Go to the old guy.

00:37:12.593 --> 00:37:13.610
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:37:13.610 --> 00:37:14.776
MARV WOLFMAN: He'd remember.

00:37:14.776 --> 00:37:15.580
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:17.455
It was called "Superman's
Return to Krypton."

00:37:17.455 --> 00:37:19.000
And I remember
reading it as a kid.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:21.680
And it just struck me because
it was a very sad story.

00:37:21.680 --> 00:37:23.560
Superman gets to
go back to Krypton.

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:26.200
He sees what a
beautiful place it was.

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:28.660
And it was also this
story about discovery.

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:32.014
It was stuff that he didn't
know about where he came from.

00:37:32.014 --> 00:37:33.430
And I think,
ultimately, we're all

00:37:33.430 --> 00:37:36.130
curious about where we
came from and stories

00:37:36.130 --> 00:37:39.340
we never would have heard as a
kid, like your crazy old aunt

00:37:39.340 --> 00:37:42.050
never told you until
you were 35 or whatever.

00:37:42.050 --> 00:37:44.140
So there was something
about that that I still

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:47.540
find very poignant to this day,
and a story that was really,

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:50.610
I think, kind of ahead of its
time for when it appeared.

00:37:53.445 --> 00:37:55.820
MARV WOLFMAN: For me, I'd also
go back to about that time

00:37:55.820 --> 00:37:59.030
period because I would not
talk about anything I did.

00:37:59.030 --> 00:38:03.330
Someone else could, I hope.

00:38:03.330 --> 00:38:04.830
SPEAKER 1: No pressure.

00:38:04.830 --> 00:38:07.580
MARV WOLFMAN: The original
"Death of Superman,"

00:38:07.580 --> 00:38:10.040
which was an amazing story
written by Jerry Siegel,

00:38:10.040 --> 00:38:12.960
the creator of
Superman in the '60s--

00:38:12.960 --> 00:38:14.800
late '50s, early
'60s, something--

00:38:14.800 --> 00:38:16.640
where Superman dies.

00:38:16.640 --> 00:38:21.800
And the story was
amazingly effective

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:24.926
because he actually dies in it.

00:38:24.926 --> 00:38:26.610
It's a great, great story.

00:38:26.610 --> 00:38:27.840
And I remember it as a kid.

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:32.937
And even now, if I read
it, it still is emotional.

00:38:32.937 --> 00:38:34.520
There were a lot of
stories back then.

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:37.850
More modern times,
"All Star Superman"

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:41.780
by Grant Morrison I thought was
a really good Superman story.

00:38:41.780 --> 00:38:43.160
Again, from left field--

00:38:43.160 --> 00:38:44.960
those are the type
of stories I like.

00:38:44.960 --> 00:38:50.070
And also "Superman for All
Seasons," by Jeph Loeb.

00:38:50.070 --> 00:38:51.980
I thought that was a
really solid story that

00:38:51.980 --> 00:38:54.830
took you in a different
place for Superman.

00:38:54.830 --> 00:38:58.730
There's been so many Superman
stories done over 80 years.

00:38:58.730 --> 00:39:02.647
It's nice when someone finds
a new tack to writing him.

00:39:02.647 --> 00:39:03.355
SPEAKER 1: Right.

00:39:03.355 --> 00:39:04.896
PAUL DINI: And I'll
go with "Whatever

00:39:04.896 --> 00:39:06.646
Happened to the Man
of Tomorrow?" by Alan.

00:39:06.646 --> 00:39:07.937
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Oh, yeah.

00:39:07.937 --> 00:39:09.590
PAUL DINI: All right,
you get that one.

00:39:09.590 --> 00:39:11.330
I'll take the first
Mxyzptlk story.

00:39:11.330 --> 00:39:13.010
I mean, I love the little jerk.

00:39:13.010 --> 00:39:16.820
And looking at that
very first one, where

00:39:16.820 --> 00:39:19.790
he's this little weird
Elmer Fudd flying man,

00:39:19.790 --> 00:39:23.010
I just thought, this is
the fun side of Superman.

00:39:23.010 --> 00:39:25.760
And I loved that story--
not every story with him.

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:29.900
But I always liked the
idea that in some way,

00:39:29.900 --> 00:39:32.450
he is to Superman what
Superman is to us.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:34.280
Superman's an advanced creature.

00:39:34.280 --> 00:39:36.910
Then one step beyond--
a few dimensions beyond

00:39:36.910 --> 00:39:39.020
is this strange
godlike creature that

00:39:39.020 --> 00:39:43.790
can either be fun or amusing or
else be absolutely terrifying.

00:39:43.790 --> 00:39:45.350
And then I'm sort of intrigued.

00:39:45.350 --> 00:39:46.460
What's beyond him?

00:39:46.460 --> 00:39:48.620
What's in the dimensions--
what scares him?

00:39:48.620 --> 00:39:51.994
And I always liked
that relationship.

00:39:51.994 --> 00:39:53.660
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Mine was "Whatever

00:39:53.660 --> 00:39:55.110
Happened to the
Man of Tomorrow?"

00:39:55.110 --> 00:39:59.300
which was Alan Moore's, like,
last testament of Superman

00:39:59.300 --> 00:40:02.947
but before crisis and you
tearing everything up.

00:40:02.947 --> 00:40:04.280
MARV WOLFMAN: I killed them all.

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:07.500
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
And that one was--

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:10.570
I think, the first time, like,
there was genuine emotion.

00:40:10.570 --> 00:40:14.210
Like, you felt like
there's loss happening.

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:18.450
And "Superman #400" is
this anniversary issue.

00:40:18.450 --> 00:40:21.710
And it's one of these great
moments in comics where they

00:40:21.710 --> 00:40:25.670
literally found, like, who would
be the most insane, coolest

00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:27.084
people to write
and draw Superman

00:40:27.084 --> 00:40:28.250
that you could ever imagine?

00:40:28.250 --> 00:40:31.840
People not even from the world
of traditional superheroes.

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:34.540
They have Steve Ditko do
Superman, and Moebius,

00:40:34.540 --> 00:40:36.020
and Brian Bolland.

00:40:36.020 --> 00:40:39.410
And it's just this celebration
of stories and artwork.

00:40:39.410 --> 00:40:40.530
And it rattled me.

00:40:40.530 --> 00:40:43.520
And when I was offered,
like, "Action #1000," which

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:48.200
is in the same vein of
that, I was, oh yeah,

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:49.730
I have to be part of that.

00:40:49.730 --> 00:40:52.490
But if you ever get a
chance, it's "Superman #400."

00:40:52.490 --> 00:40:54.940
It also comes with a
Superman portfolio.

00:40:54.940 --> 00:40:56.510
So you get, like,
a large version

00:40:56.510 --> 00:40:58.790
of all these beautiful
images of Superman.

00:40:58.790 --> 00:41:02.000
And it just-- everything you'd
ever want out of the Superman

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:03.230
experience right there.

00:41:03.230 --> 00:41:05.510
And the first Superman
movie, Richard Donner.

00:41:05.510 --> 00:41:07.910
Just showed my
5-year-old son the movie,

00:41:07.910 --> 00:41:10.190
thinking he wouldn't make
about 10 minutes into it.

00:41:10.190 --> 00:41:11.780
Like, I thought he'd bail.

00:41:11.780 --> 00:41:12.770
Riveted.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:15.080
Couldn't take his
eyes off of the movie.

00:41:15.080 --> 00:41:17.162
So it's a great experience.

00:41:17.162 --> 00:41:17.870
SPEAKER 1: Great.

00:41:17.870 --> 00:41:20.936
So who wants to go first?

00:41:20.936 --> 00:41:21.522
Oh.

00:41:21.522 --> 00:41:23.230
I'm going to throw
this to you awkwardly.

00:41:23.230 --> 00:41:23.700
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:41:23.700 --> 00:41:24.408
I'll [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:24.408 --> 00:41:25.880
SPEAKER 1: So here it goes.

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:26.960
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: What is that?

00:41:26.960 --> 00:41:28.043
AUDIENCE: That is awkward.

00:41:28.043 --> 00:41:32.450
SPEAKER 1: That is the way we
ask Google questions awkwardly

00:41:32.450 --> 00:41:34.220
because we like to
embarrass people.

00:41:34.220 --> 00:41:35.000
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: All right.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:36.833
AUDIENCE: We like to
really embarrass people

00:41:36.833 --> 00:41:38.090
who can't throw, specifically.

00:41:38.090 --> 00:41:38.715
SPEAKER 1: Yes.

00:41:38.715 --> 00:41:39.860
[CHUCKLES]

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:41.720
AUDIENCE: So my
question for you guys

00:41:41.720 --> 00:41:44.330
is, how do you deal
with considering

00:41:44.330 --> 00:41:47.570
how long the Superman
comic has been around,

00:41:47.570 --> 00:41:50.000
how do you deal with
keeping it consistent

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.280
and not conflicting
inside of itself?

00:41:53.280 --> 00:41:55.970
Like, did you have to consider
that when you're writing?

00:41:55.970 --> 00:41:59.090
Or is there somebody who
reads it later and says,

00:41:59.090 --> 00:42:01.611
you totally can't say
that because it really

00:42:01.611 --> 00:42:03.110
conflicts with this
other thing that

00:42:03.110 --> 00:42:04.700
was said like 30 years ago?

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:06.620
Or does it just
kind of work out?

00:42:09.161 --> 00:42:11.660
DAN JURGENS: Well, I was lucky
because when I first started,

00:42:11.660 --> 00:42:15.380
Superman had had a new starting
point, where they just said,

00:42:15.380 --> 00:42:17.240
OK, we're starting clean.

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:21.710
And that was John Byrne
and Marv and Jerry Ordway

00:42:21.710 --> 00:42:23.900
who relaunched the franchise.

00:42:23.900 --> 00:42:26.120
So I was fortunate enough
to be able to come on

00:42:26.120 --> 00:42:28.950
and say we had a
fairly clean slate.

00:42:28.950 --> 00:42:31.300
And I think that's
important to do.

00:42:31.300 --> 00:42:34.860
It's only fair because
to strictly adhere

00:42:34.860 --> 00:42:37.700
to 80 years of
publishing history

00:42:37.700 --> 00:42:41.840
is really, really hard to
do and totally impractical,

00:42:41.840 --> 00:42:43.310
I might add, I think.

00:42:43.310 --> 00:42:45.320
MARV WOLFMAN: I
think if you worry

00:42:45.320 --> 00:42:47.690
about making sure
every story fits

00:42:47.690 --> 00:42:55.400
into some place in continuity,
you're not able to expand out.

00:42:55.400 --> 00:42:59.030
The box that you're in keeps
getting smaller and smaller.

00:42:59.030 --> 00:43:01.610
I think you have to take
the spirit of the character,

00:43:01.610 --> 00:43:05.360
the idea of the character, and
the approach of what you're

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:07.490
trying to do to
tell more stories,

00:43:07.490 --> 00:43:10.470
and not worry about every
little detail of the past.

00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:11.960
It's fiction.

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:14.870
No one's going to come and
say, that's not what happened.

00:43:14.870 --> 00:43:15.370
I was there.

00:43:15.370 --> 00:43:15.850
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Yes, they will.

00:43:15.850 --> 00:43:16.530
That's what Twitter [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:16.530 --> 00:43:16.800
AUDIENCE: Are you sure?

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:17.105
MARV WOLFMAN: Yeah.

00:43:17.105 --> 00:43:17.650
AUDIENCE: I'm pretty sure--

00:43:17.650 --> 00:43:17.960
SPEAKER 1: That's the internet.

00:43:17.960 --> 00:43:19.370
AUDIENCE: --people at
Comic-Con probably would.

00:43:19.370 --> 00:43:20.786
BRIAN MICHAEL
BENDIS: Yeah, what I

00:43:20.786 --> 00:43:23.390
do is I ignore everyone else's
work and just barrel ahead

00:43:23.390 --> 00:43:23.890
straight.

00:43:23.890 --> 00:43:25.140
And it works out great for me.

00:43:25.140 --> 00:43:26.807
MARV WOLFMAN: That's
already on Twitter.

00:43:26.807 --> 00:43:27.931
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:43:27.931 --> 00:43:28.440
Honestly--

00:43:28.440 --> 00:43:29.570
MARV WOLFMAN: Brian says--

00:43:29.570 --> 00:43:30.611
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: No.

00:43:30.611 --> 00:43:31.910
You know what the key is?

00:43:31.910 --> 00:43:34.252
You live like how you're living.

00:43:34.252 --> 00:43:35.210
You live in the moment.

00:43:35.210 --> 00:43:36.200
You live in the now.

00:43:36.200 --> 00:43:38.170
Like you, yourself,
you live in the moment.

00:43:38.170 --> 00:43:40.900
You're not sitting there
living your continuity that

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:41.880
brought you to this--

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:44.490
I'm not sitting here with a big
thought balloon over my head,

00:43:44.490 --> 00:43:46.580
thinking about what happened
to me in the eighth grade that

00:43:46.580 --> 00:43:47.330
led me here.

00:43:47.330 --> 00:43:49.160
It's in the moment.

00:43:49.160 --> 00:43:51.620
And when things happen
that relate to your past,

00:43:51.620 --> 00:43:54.360
then you bring them up
when they're appropriate.

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:58.670
But it's a trap that comic book
writers can get sucked into,

00:43:58.670 --> 00:44:00.410
where you think you
have to acknowledge

00:44:00.410 --> 00:44:04.070
everything that ever happened to
this character at every moment.

00:44:04.070 --> 00:44:08.000
Or if, like I said,
like, if I tell my wife

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:09.200
I loved her today--

00:44:09.200 --> 00:44:09.860
wait a second.

00:44:09.860 --> 00:44:13.210
35 years ago, you told a girl
in high school you loved her.

00:44:13.210 --> 00:44:17.640
Like, that's how comic book
fans sometimes act at you.

00:44:17.640 --> 00:44:19.090
Like, wait a minute.

00:44:19.090 --> 00:44:22.150
Like, well, yeah, that was
true then, and it's true here.

00:44:22.150 --> 00:44:23.000
So anyway.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.690
SPEAKER 1: Is that how you
reply to Twitter followers?

00:44:25.690 --> 00:44:27.890
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
No, I ignore it.

00:44:27.890 --> 00:44:30.340
No, it's part of the game.

00:44:30.340 --> 00:44:33.290
I actually like the
part of the game where

00:44:33.290 --> 00:44:34.490
they go, hey, wait a minute.

00:44:34.490 --> 00:44:36.470
I'm the resident
expert of Superman.

00:44:36.470 --> 00:44:38.540
And I'm about to tell you
what you've done wrong.

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:40.320
I like being there for them.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:41.180
[LAUGHING]

00:44:41.180 --> 00:44:41.860
No, I do.

00:44:41.860 --> 00:44:43.631
Like, I was writing "X-Men."

00:44:43.631 --> 00:44:45.130
And someone who's
read every "X-Men"

00:44:45.130 --> 00:44:46.730
wants to come give
me the business--

00:44:46.730 --> 00:44:48.244
what a great time
they're having.

00:44:48.244 --> 00:44:50.160
They've read all their
comics, and now they're

00:44:50.160 --> 00:44:51.118
giving me the business.

00:44:51.118 --> 00:44:53.600
Anyway.

00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:56.390
AUDIENCE: My question was,
one of my favorite iterations

00:44:56.390 --> 00:44:59.270
of Superman is when he shows up
in a "Justice League America"

00:44:59.270 --> 00:45:01.580
episode where it's
Bizarro World.

00:45:01.580 --> 00:45:04.640
And essentially, all of the
Justice League characters

00:45:04.640 --> 00:45:08.690
are evil versions of themselves,
or at least morally defunct

00:45:08.690 --> 00:45:10.090
versions of themselves.

00:45:10.090 --> 00:45:13.970
And in that episode, Superman
lobotomizes Darkseid.

00:45:13.970 --> 00:45:16.940
And I guess my
question is, that was

00:45:16.940 --> 00:45:18.920
one of my favorite
iterations of Superman

00:45:18.920 --> 00:45:21.590
because it showed
how hope fails.

00:45:21.590 --> 00:45:26.160
Like, hope does diminish
after a period of time.

00:45:26.160 --> 00:45:29.390
And that was kind of what that
Bizarro Justice League was

00:45:29.390 --> 00:45:31.280
the amalgamation
of, was their world

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:34.700
had gone to such a dark point
that they just said, screw it.

00:45:34.700 --> 00:45:37.550
We're just going to start
lobotomizing the enemy, right?

00:45:37.550 --> 00:45:39.590
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Well, it
depends what you're hoping for.

00:45:39.590 --> 00:45:41.030
Like, if you're
hoping for a lobotomy,

00:45:41.030 --> 00:45:42.196
it was a very hopeful story.

00:45:42.196 --> 00:45:43.580
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:45:43.580 --> 00:45:46.640
I guess my question is, is like,
that really resonated with me

00:45:46.640 --> 00:45:49.760
because as real human
beings dealing with the day

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:52.400
to day, we do lose hope,
even in the small things

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:54.710
and sometimes very
easily in the big things.

00:45:54.710 --> 00:45:56.210
And so that really
resonated with me

00:45:56.210 --> 00:45:58.400
that, like, somebody as,
like you guys were saying,

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:01.730
a symbol of hope like Superman,
that in that iteration

00:46:01.730 --> 00:46:03.345
of his story, he just quickly--

00:46:03.345 --> 00:46:05.720
and, like, I think it's the
Batman from the regular world

00:46:05.720 --> 00:46:06.620
sees that happening.

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:09.905
And he's like, holy sh-- like,
he's lobotomizing people.

00:46:09.905 --> 00:46:11.780
We really have something
to worry about here.

00:46:11.780 --> 00:46:13.470
Like, this is a serious threat.

00:46:13.470 --> 00:46:15.380
Do you guys ever see
Superman going back

00:46:15.380 --> 00:46:17.171
in a direction like
that, where his hope is

00:46:17.171 --> 00:46:20.330
so on the hairline,
where he's dealing

00:46:20.330 --> 00:46:23.690
with something that the world
itself or, like, the city

00:46:23.690 --> 00:46:26.420
or even other superheroes
look to him and worry,

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:29.480
because if he loses hope, not
only is it a symbol of hope

00:46:29.480 --> 00:46:31.520
crashing, but he might
really be something

00:46:31.520 --> 00:46:32.780
to worry about himself?

00:46:32.780 --> 00:46:33.310
PAUL DINI: Well, I think--

00:46:33.310 --> 00:46:34.430
AUDIENCE: And that was
really kind of cool to me.

00:46:34.430 --> 00:46:36.971
PAUL DINI: I think stories like
that are important because it

00:46:36.971 --> 00:46:40.760
gives the heroes from the
real world-- our world--

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:44.510
a mirror to what could happen
if they do cross that line.

00:46:44.510 --> 00:46:47.750
And it's like "It's a
Wonderful Life," where

00:46:47.750 --> 00:46:52.100
you see what his life
could be like if he did,

00:46:52.100 --> 00:46:53.730
in fact, lose hope.

00:46:53.730 --> 00:46:56.715
I think with Superman, the
challenge is there to make sure

00:46:56.715 --> 00:46:58.340
that he never loses
that because that's

00:46:58.340 --> 00:47:00.740
what makes him different
from everybody else.

00:47:00.740 --> 00:47:01.870
That's the ultimate test.

00:47:01.870 --> 00:47:05.930
It's to keep that hope alive for
everybody else and for himself.

00:47:05.930 --> 00:47:07.040
MARV WOLFMAN: Yeah.

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:10.900
That's, Paul, one
of a two-part story.

00:47:10.900 --> 00:47:13.220
AUDIENCE: I mean, I've
seen [INAUDIBLE] episode.

00:47:13.220 --> 00:47:14.620
But it still was brilliant.

00:47:14.620 --> 00:47:15.729
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Good answer, by the way.

00:47:15.729 --> 00:47:16.479
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:47:16.479 --> 00:47:18.723
[CHUCKLING]

00:47:20.220 --> 00:47:23.330
AUDIENCE: So I
really love Superman.

00:47:23.330 --> 00:47:25.790
He was my first favorite
superhero as a kid.

00:47:25.790 --> 00:47:29.120
So this is a really
cool talk for me.

00:47:29.120 --> 00:47:32.450
So my question is, one of
the things that I think

00:47:32.450 --> 00:47:35.600
makes Superman more
challenging in some ways

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:39.440
is that he doesn't have some
of that internal conflict

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:42.710
that you see in a Batman or
a Spider-Man or something,

00:47:42.710 --> 00:47:44.750
where he's really,
really struggling

00:47:44.750 --> 00:47:48.120
with his own insecurities
in a lot of places.

00:47:48.120 --> 00:47:50.780
And I think there have been a
lot of really interesting takes

00:47:50.780 --> 00:47:55.100
on that over the years,
from, Paul, when you brought

00:47:55.100 --> 00:47:57.170
up earlier Superman
confronting, like,

00:47:57.170 --> 00:48:00.260
a real-world situation
where his powers don't apply

00:48:00.260 --> 00:48:01.790
or things like that.

00:48:01.790 --> 00:48:06.170
And so I was curious,
without that level

00:48:06.170 --> 00:48:12.470
of internal conflict, what
is your favorite way that you

00:48:12.470 --> 00:48:17.810
or somebody else has approached
that kind of thing, of finding

00:48:17.810 --> 00:48:22.310
a conflict, finding a challenge
for Superman that's not related

00:48:22.310 --> 00:48:24.290
to that internal struggle?

00:48:24.290 --> 00:48:28.100
MARV WOLFMAN: Well,
for me, I think

00:48:28.100 --> 00:48:31.070
what you do with Superman
is his internal conflict is

00:48:31.070 --> 00:48:37.080
about what is the best way
of solving this problem?

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:39.770
How do I do it with the
least collateral damage?

00:48:39.770 --> 00:48:42.560
How do I create a
situation that makes

00:48:42.560 --> 00:48:47.480
this work, rather than, oh, Lois
didn't want to date me tonight.

00:48:47.480 --> 00:48:49.880
That's a very different
type of thing.

00:48:49.880 --> 00:48:54.050
His problems deal
with how to do his job

00:48:54.050 --> 00:48:55.910
and how to do it the
best way possible,

00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:57.920
because he is only a person.

00:48:57.920 --> 00:48:59.160
He may have a lot of powers.

00:48:59.160 --> 00:49:00.230
But he's only a person.

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:02.960
And he's going to have questions
on is he doing the right thing.

00:49:02.960 --> 00:49:04.170
How do I do it?

00:49:04.170 --> 00:49:05.780
How do I make it work?

00:49:05.780 --> 00:49:10.100
And he's going to keep trying
to find the best way that nobody

00:49:10.100 --> 00:49:13.010
gets hurt in the process.

00:49:13.010 --> 00:49:15.170
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Yeah, I found myself

00:49:15.170 --> 00:49:18.020
looking for my
relatability with Superman.

00:49:18.020 --> 00:49:23.191
And the one internal struggle
I found for myself is I'm

00:49:23.191 --> 00:49:23.690
a father.

00:49:23.690 --> 00:49:24.619
I have four kids.

00:49:24.619 --> 00:49:25.410
I have little kids.

00:49:25.410 --> 00:49:26.450
I have big kids.

00:49:26.450 --> 00:49:30.110
And one of the hardest
things for me for parenting

00:49:30.110 --> 00:49:33.410
is you have to be on
your game all day.

00:49:33.410 --> 00:49:36.301
You can't-- today, I'm going
to just be the worst version

00:49:36.301 --> 00:49:36.800
of myself.

00:49:36.800 --> 00:49:38.758
No, you have to be the
best version of yourself

00:49:38.758 --> 00:49:41.990
like every day, or
at least try, right?

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:43.450
So you're, like, every day.

00:49:43.450 --> 00:49:45.520
And it could be exhausting.

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:46.159
Like--

00:49:46.159 --> 00:49:47.450
AUDIENCE: I have a 9-month-old.

00:49:47.450 --> 00:49:48.840
So I'm starting to
figure that out.

00:49:48.840 --> 00:49:49.670
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Oh, yeah, well,

00:49:49.670 --> 00:49:52.520
when they can walk and talk, and
they're actually watching you,

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:55.430
like, looking for hypocrisy--
like there's an age at, like, 7

00:49:55.430 --> 00:49:57.742
or 8, where they walk around
the house going, well,

00:49:57.742 --> 00:49:58.700
I didn't get any candy.

00:49:58.700 --> 00:50:00.700
I'm going to watch and
see if you get any candy.

00:50:00.700 --> 00:50:04.525
And so there's,
like, just general--

00:50:04.525 --> 00:50:06.350
and I see Superman
has to do that.

00:50:06.350 --> 00:50:08.750
He has to be Superman every day.

00:50:08.750 --> 00:50:11.810
You can't just-- today, I'm
going to walk around in my robe

00:50:11.810 --> 00:50:15.960
and-- no, I have to, like,
live up to this every day.

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:18.830
And that's the connection
I feel like as adults,

00:50:18.830 --> 00:50:19.890
we have to live up to a
certain responsibility.

00:50:19.890 --> 00:50:20.405
DAN JURGENS: Oh, yeah.

00:50:20.405 --> 00:50:21.290
PAUL DINI: Yeah, absolutely.

00:50:21.290 --> 00:50:23.664
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: And if
we blow it once, we blew it.

00:50:23.664 --> 00:50:24.350
That's it.

00:50:24.350 --> 00:50:27.350
DAN JURGENS: I've
always had this thing

00:50:27.350 --> 00:50:29.570
for a different
Superman story, where,

00:50:29.570 --> 00:50:32.090
like, if there had
never been a Superman,

00:50:32.090 --> 00:50:33.810
how would you do
it kind of thing.

00:50:33.810 --> 00:50:36.500
And it was we pick up on
Superman when he's, like,

00:50:36.500 --> 00:50:37.740
42 years old.

00:50:37.740 --> 00:50:41.120
And even at then,
he's barely a myth

00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:44.900
because he was someone
throughout that first 25 years

00:50:44.900 --> 00:50:47.840
of him being Superman, never
revealed himself to the public.

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:50.870
He only ever would have come
out like once every three years

00:50:50.870 --> 00:50:52.850
when the world
demanded it somehow.

00:50:52.850 --> 00:50:54.320
And then ultimately,
the conflict

00:50:54.320 --> 00:50:57.620
would have been exactly when
do you choose to get involved?

00:50:57.620 --> 00:50:59.630
Because that, to
me, is something

00:50:59.630 --> 00:51:00.740
we all face every day.

00:51:00.740 --> 00:51:02.990
How often have we
walked down the street

00:51:02.990 --> 00:51:05.240
and seen something
happening across the street

00:51:05.240 --> 00:51:07.910
where we wondered, should
we get involved or not?

00:51:07.910 --> 00:51:10.820
That woman-- she's really kind
of being hard on her child.

00:51:10.820 --> 00:51:12.200
Should I go say something?

00:51:12.200 --> 00:51:13.880
That's the conflict
for Superman, which

00:51:13.880 --> 00:51:15.590
is when do you get involved?

00:51:15.590 --> 00:51:17.240
And exactly how far do you go?

00:51:17.240 --> 00:51:19.730
And you mentioned
this earlier, which

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:21.830
is Superman doesn't
tell people what to do.

00:51:21.830 --> 00:51:23.750
He hopes to inspire.

00:51:23.750 --> 00:51:26.120
And so you start to
build around that.

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:29.210
And there are so many stories
that you can pull out of that.

00:51:29.210 --> 00:51:32.450
So, yeah.

00:51:32.450 --> 00:51:33.840
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:51:33.840 --> 00:51:35.020
I obviously have a question.

00:51:35.020 --> 00:51:36.490
But before that, I want
to say, thank you all.

00:51:36.490 --> 00:51:38.020
Like, you all have
amazing contributions.

00:51:38.020 --> 00:51:39.686
And nobody says thank
you enough to you.

00:51:39.686 --> 00:51:42.820
So, like, thank every one
of you, like, so much.

00:51:42.820 --> 00:51:45.160
My question kind of
pulls from, like,

00:51:45.160 --> 00:51:49.300
Dan's recent storyline in
action around "The Oz Effect."

00:51:49.300 --> 00:51:51.850
Do you think we
deserve Superman?

00:51:59.680 --> 00:52:02.230
DAN JURGENS: I sort of wrestle
with that all the time,

00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:07.730
because I think that one of
the things about politics

00:52:07.730 --> 00:52:10.790
right now, without
getting into either party,

00:52:10.790 --> 00:52:13.640
is more and more
I ask myself, why

00:52:13.640 --> 00:52:15.860
would any good person do this?

00:52:15.860 --> 00:52:17.520
Because we punish them.

00:52:17.520 --> 00:52:20.720
And I think we see that
across-- whoever signs up

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:22.790
to run for office
basically knows

00:52:22.790 --> 00:52:25.700
they're going to get nuked
by the other side, right?

00:52:25.700 --> 00:52:28.070
And so I ask myself
that all the time.

00:52:28.070 --> 00:52:30.650
When do we find out
that we do or do not

00:52:30.650 --> 00:52:34.050
deserve someone who is trying
to act on behalf of us?

00:52:34.050 --> 00:52:36.552
And I think that's a
fascinating theme to play with.

00:52:36.552 --> 00:52:38.290
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Well, I'd say yes.

00:52:38.290 --> 00:52:39.060
DAN JURGENS: Yeah,
I would hope so.

00:52:39.060 --> 00:52:39.540
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Yeah.

00:52:39.540 --> 00:52:40.750
We do deserve it.

00:52:40.750 --> 00:52:42.699
We don't deserve the
opposition research.

00:52:42.699 --> 00:52:43.490
DAN JURGENS: Right.

00:52:43.490 --> 00:52:43.990
Yeah.

00:52:43.990 --> 00:52:46.390
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
But, yeah, we do deserve--

00:52:46.390 --> 00:52:48.930
DAN JURGENS: Yeah, but the
question is, who would step up?

00:52:48.930 --> 00:52:49.720
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
No, absolutely.

00:52:49.720 --> 00:52:51.540
Who would step up,
like finding out

00:52:51.540 --> 00:52:52.830
what you found out this week?

00:52:52.830 --> 00:52:53.160
DAN JURGENS: Yeah.

00:52:53.160 --> 00:52:55.159
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Like with the analyticals?

00:52:55.159 --> 00:52:57.310
I'm sure you guys are
dealing with that.

00:52:57.310 --> 00:53:00.340
Like, who would want to
put yourself under that?

00:53:00.340 --> 00:53:02.610
Like, that that's
even more intense.

00:53:02.610 --> 00:53:04.440
Like, the first
thing was intense.

00:53:04.440 --> 00:53:05.730
This is even more intense.

00:53:05.730 --> 00:53:07.140
So, yeah, I don't know.

00:53:07.140 --> 00:53:09.670
But I'd remove that
from the equation.

00:53:09.670 --> 00:53:12.021
And just someone shows
up and goes, screw it.

00:53:12.021 --> 00:53:13.270
This is the right thing to do.

00:53:13.270 --> 00:53:13.820
I'm going to do it.

00:53:13.820 --> 00:53:13.950
Yeah--

00:53:13.950 --> 00:53:14.220
DAN JURGENS: Right.

00:53:14.220 --> 00:53:16.011
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
--we do deserve that.

00:53:16.011 --> 00:53:17.050
DAN JURGENS: Yes.

00:53:17.050 --> 00:53:17.950
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS:
Paul doesn't think so.

00:53:17.950 --> 00:53:18.892
PAUL DINI: [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:18.892 --> 00:53:21.100
BRIAN MICHAEL BENDIS: Paul
thinks we deserve to burn.

00:53:21.100 --> 00:53:22.661
He likes to write the Joker.

00:53:22.661 --> 00:53:23.910
PAUL DINI: A little bit, yeah.

00:53:23.910 --> 00:53:25.630
